<div id="review_1590141630" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1590141630" />
    <a title="Guy Austin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38544962-guy-austin"><img alt="Guy Austin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1465936953p2/38544962.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1590141630?book_show_action=true">Mar 25, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Guy Austin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Guy Austin" href="/user/show/38544962-guy-austin">Guy Austin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780395320471" href="/book/show/761450.Shoeless_Joe">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38544962-guy-austin?shelf=books-on-shelf-read">books-on-shelf-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1590141630" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1074550290155774501">So, Ok I am no critic – This is one book I have wanted to read for some time. So much so that I bought a first addition and hold it high on my shelf displayed prominently. With the 2016 season just about to start I thought it was a good a time as ever to pick up what many consider one of the best novels written around the game of baseball. <br/><br/>Honestly at first – I was a little disappointed. I am not sure what I expected. I guess we bring expectations with us that cannot reasonably be met. That unre</span>
  <span id="freeText1074550290155774501" style="display:none">So, Ok I am no critic – This is one book I have wanted to read for some time. So much so that I bought a first addition and hold it high on my shelf displayed prominently. With the 2016 season just about to start I thought it was a good a time as ever to pick up what many consider one of the best novels written around the game of baseball. <br /><br />Honestly at first – I was a little disappointed. I am not sure what I expected. I guess we bring expectations with us that cannot reasonably be met. That unrealistic expectation can color our perception of things as they become reality. As I got into the novel it began to pick up steam. As it progresses I start to “get it” There is something special here. <br /><br />It is clear W.P. Kinsella has a love for the game, perhaps even more than I do. (That is hard to believe.) He writes about it in such a way that perhaps only the true worshipers of the game can understand. At times it can be a bit over the top. When he describes the way a character watches the game it is clear they are caught up in the fluid motions on the perimeter of the action just as much as the crack of the bat or the tag of the runner. I think the game itself is better developed as a character than some of the actual persons in the novel. <br /><br />There are some great nuggets in this book. One especially used in many documentaries on the game including Burns’ amazing Baseball Epic. The problem for me was, at times, it's hard to connect to some of the characters and story line. I did not feel the emotion. The story as a whole is great, but there were a few parts that did not quite fit for me. It was like seeing a repaired garment with the stitching off, in such a way, that it does not quite look right… and I cannot stop from staring at it.<br /><br />I gave it 4 stars but if I am being honest it is probably 3.5 for me. It is truly worth the read. It was a pretty quick read as well. <br /><br />I also thought contrary to the thought that "he" was Shoeless Joe, the announcer speaks of when saying, "If you build it, he will come." I believe "he" was someone else entirely. <br /><br />I also noted that Kinsella can write some of the longest sentences I have ever read. I read them wondering what Mrs. Iacoboni, my 7th grade English teacher, might have to say about them. <br /><br />I think that Dr. Graham had many of the better lines, besides the one by the fictional incarnation of J.D. Salinger that are well known near the end. And it is one of those lines I leave you with…<br /><br />“Once you’ve been touched by the land, the wind never blows so cold again, because your love files the edges off it.” <br />― W.P. Kinsella, Shoeless Joe<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1074550290155774501" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

